A favoritism capitalism, American-style
Do you remember the crisis in East Asia? When the US Department of the Treasury and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on a favoritism capitalism, a lack of transparency, and an inefficient government?
Nations were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting control firms, to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them to manage their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed faster than any other region - and with greater stability - over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal lends new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "We sow what we reap" and "One must be without fault to criticize others".
Enron used large accounting schemes and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to acquire influence and power, shape US energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Favoritism capitalism is not new, nor is it the sole domain of any one party.
The former US Secretary of the Treasury, Robert Rubin, would have attempted to influence the current government to intervene on behalf of Enron in the contentious conflict in India.
When it was in office, it intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards board tried to clean up the accounting of the companies at the expense of senior executives.
It is partly thanks to him that the effort to make corporate accounting more transparent has been hindered.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is only a thin veil for the well-being of old companies: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed indicates the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it shows the importance of a free press that can stop abuses, but reduce them.
When the press started looking into Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
The campaign contributions were not just a matter of public interest, but an investment.
Like most Enron investments, everything went well in the short term, but did not produce results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Certainly some concerning politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the argument in favor of a reform on campaign financing and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by business interests which can, in fact, buy elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to release information that would confirm the role of business interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons relate to economics, particularly information economics.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals to be provided to allocate resources effectively, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The control of accounts is intended to set limits on potential abuses.
But who will keep the guardians ?
Who will control the account controllers ?
We are counting on motivations to be enormous.
The auditors want to preserve their reputation.
But the relation between advisory practices and account control practices brings other perverted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavourable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former president of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within account control firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls may be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unknown hero of the debacle.
But the account control firms and their corporate clients - which is not surprising, given the cabal that developed - have sharply attacked his proposal to separate advisory and account control activities.
What Levitt understood - and what the Enron debacle so clearly showed - is that motivations are important, but that unimpeded markets cannot by themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of combinations that Enron was implementing.
The new economy - and its new, complex financial instruments - puts into value the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to blur.
Instead of facing the problems, American business systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time consists of finding the right balance between government and market.
The current state will claim that Enron is an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud and that those who violate these laws must suffer the consequences and will suffer them.
But the great majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its accountants declare that its central practices conformed to the law and that thousands of other enterprises act in the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received reflects sufficiently the economic situation of the company.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at the present time.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we'll never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical norms.
But we cannot count on them when so many people in the world see nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage the conflicts of interest, but we observe that they can manage them in their own interests.
But even when the evidence of this type of abuse becomes obvious, new places of abuse are created time and time again - take the American repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investments.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unfettered markets.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the opposite extreme.
The challenge to be met is to achieve the right balance.
